  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Particle acceleration — oblique shocks</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Oblique-shock acceleration</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Research</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Educational level:</th><td>Research</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Key Papers:</th><td>Kirk et al.; Bell (2011)</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Oblique shocks are shocks where the magnetic field has a non-zero angle to the shock normal. Obliquity strongly influences particle reflection, injection into DSA, and the resulting spectral slope. Guide-field strength and turbulence level modify acceleration efficiency.</p>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>Recollimation shocks are typically oblique. 2603.16647 treats obliquity approximately via parameterised downstream pressure and jump conditions, but notes that full oblique-shock microphysics (e.g., anisotropic scattering, shock drift acceleration) can alter spectra and efficiency — motivating further kinetic and simulation studies.</p>

    <h2>Key references</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Kirk 1989; Gieseler 1999; Bell 2011 — theoretical and numerical studies of oblique shocks and their effect on acceleration.</li>
      <li>Reville et al. — modern discussions of guide-field and obliquity effects (cited in 2603.16647).</li>
    </ol>

